  "articleSummary": "This tutorial argues that reliably extracting URLs from unstructured text requires a permissive, two-step strategy: first casting a wide net to capture potential URL-like strings, then applying secondary validation. Centered on a reusable ~120-byte JavaScript regex pattern, the article systematically dissects the expression into five capture groups corresponding to standard URL anatomy (protocol, domain, path, query, and fragment). Written in a practical, step-by-step tutorial tone, it uses metaphors like \"whack-a-mole\" and \"casting a wide net\" to frame the extraction challenge and solution. The intended audience is developers, data engineers, and web scrapers seeking a robust, ready-to-deploy regex pattern for initial URL extraction in JavaScript environments.",
